YOUTUBE QpmsftF2We4
A clay cylinder covered in Akkadian cuneiform script, damaged and broken, the Cyrus Cylinder is a powerful symbol of religious tolerance and multi-culturalism. In this enthralling talk Neil MacGregor, Director of the British Museum, traces 2600 years of Middle Eastern history through this single object.
Neil MacGregor is the director of the British Museum and the author of A History of the World In 100 Objects, both the radio series and the book derived from it.

MacGregor was born in Glasgow. At the age of nine, he first saw Salvador Dal√≠'s Christ of Saint John of the Cross, newly acquired by Glasgow's Kelvingrove Art Gallery, which had a profound effect on him and sparked his lifelong interest in art. MacGregor was educated at Glasgow Academy and then read modern languages at New College, Oxford, where he is now an honorary fellow.
Neil MacGregor is an art historian and the director of the British Museum and the author of A History of the World In 100 Objects, both the radio series and the book derived from it.

MacGregor was born in Glasgow. At the age of nine, he first saw Salvador Dal√≠'s Christ of Saint John of the Cross, newly acquired by Glasgow's Kelvingrove Art Gallery, which had a profound effect on him and sparked his lifelong interest in art. MacGregor was educated at Glasgow Academy and then read modern languages at New College, Oxford, where he is now an honorary fellow.

He studied philosophy at the √âcole Normale Sup√©rieure in Paris and Law at Edinburgh University. Despite being called to the bar in 1972, MacGregor next decided to take an art history degree. 

From 1975 to 1981, MacGregor taught History of Art and Architecture at the University of Reading. He left to assume the editorship of The Burlington Magazine. He oversaw the transfer of the magazine from the Thomson Corporation to an independent and charitable status.
In 2010, MacGregor presented a series on BBC Radio 4 and the World Service entitled A History of the World in 100 Objects, based on objects from the British Museum's collection.

From September 2010 to January 2011 the British Museum lent the ancient Persian Cyrus Cylinder to an exhibition in Tehran. This was seen by at least a million visitors by the Museum's estimation, more than any loan exhibition to the United Kingdom had attracted since the Treasures of Tutankhamun exhibition in 1972. On 4 November 2010 MacGregor was appointed to the Order of Merit by Queen Elizabeth II. On 25 March 2013 MacGregor was appointed an Honorary Officer of the Order of Australia (AO) by the Governor General of Australia Quentin Bryce. Shakespeare's Restless World was published in 2013.
In 2010, MacGregor presented a series on BBC Radio 4 and the World Service entitled [[A History of the World in 100 Objects]], based on objects from the British Museum's collection.
